content:
✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: A very easy and fun clash! Square rooting isn't even necessary here, because checking whether a square root of a sum is more than 9 can be changed to checking whether the sum is more than 81 :)
I can see how this can be interesing for Shortest mode as well!

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Very well suited for clash of code.

My solution looks a lot like yours. I can see a lot of interesting ways for shortest as well.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Super fast to implement.  Nearly took as much time to type it.  Shortest mode took a little longer.

Here is my solution

for i in range(int(input())):print(["WAIT","OPEN"][sum([float(j)**2 for j in input().split()])>81])
Nice theme and very good idea

If a parashute can be open only once, the output should be a single value meaning when to open a parashute.
E.g., every measurement will have a kind of "id" or "index" and the output should be to provide only this:

Input:
10
1 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000
2 0.0000 0.0000 1.0900
3 0.0000 0.0000 2.1800
4 0.0000 0.0000 3.2700
5 0.0000 0.0000 4.3600
6 0.0000 0.0000 5.4500
7 0.0000 0.0000 6.5400
8 0.0000 0.0000 7.6300
9 0.0000 0.0000 8.7200
10 0.0000 0.0000 9.8100

Output: 
10
Love the space and physics theme.
Small modification, the interest of the exercise is to manipulate floats, the power function and square root.
Although it seems very clunky and difficult, it is still an interesting problem. Improve some of the explanations (to make it a doable CoC) and then I'll approve of it!)
This one relies a bit too heavily on knowing physics formulas to be a fun clash. Thenagain giving away the formula takes out all the effort from it.
